{Lucy. Bangor Dec. 6. 1854}
{Dunbarton Dec. 8. 1854}
at the melancholy view you take of the loss of life by shipwreck because it is "such a world of work to rear even one!" That view of the subject never occurred to me before, but really I think it is very rational to lay considerable stress on that part. Doubtless you regret such calamities for other reasons! Letters from Charles received today tell us he is on the way home. We shall expect him every day. I wish the dear Isaac was as near to you. What a comfort it is, with our whole hearts to trust our dear absent ones, and all the dear ones to the watch of "an eye that never sleeps!" I am sorry for your back. Had you not better try Maria's sitz baths? 

Mother says she loves you very much and thinks of you very often if she does not write. I think she will write soon. We are having fine, cold,  bracing weather now, though it has been very mild most of the fall. The course of lectures this winter I would love to attend. I shall try if I am possibly well enough, to hear Henry Wm. Beecher & Lucy Stowe for the novelty of it. Mr. Chapin from N.Y. Theodore Parker, Starr King,
